<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEIL BUSH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In response to "Bush's Son Defends Role at S &amp; L," front page, May 24: 
</P>
<P>
Neil Bush is a chip off the old block. His responses to congressional committee 
questions set a new family standard for rhetorical obfuscation. 
</P>
<P>
Q: How do you explain the gift of $100,000 from Kenneth Good? A: It wasn't a 
gift. It was a loan "that was never meant to be repaid." 
</P>
<P>
Q: Why is that not a conflict of interest? A: "It just isn't." 
</P>
<P>
Q: Did you have any financial interest in any of Bill Walters' business? A: No. 
"He was a partner in my business, but I wasn't a partner in any of his 
businesses." 
</P>
<P>
Q: Why did you not mention the loan from Kenneth Good on a conflict-of-interest 
form required of directors? A: Because "it sounds a little fishy." 
</P>
<P>
Read my lips, Neil. It smells a little fishy too. 
</P>
<P>
HERBERT L. WEINBERG 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
