<P>
CALIFORNIA IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
SACRAMENTO; 
</P>
<P>
3 CHARGED WITH DEFRAUDING STATE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A former accounting clerk with the legislative analyst's office and two other 
Sacramento residents have been arrested on charges they defrauded the state out 
of $119,000. The attorney general's office said the three concocted an 
elaborate plot to forge state checks and bill the state for airline tickets for 
trips that were not taken. 
</P>
<P>
Charged with conspiracy to embezzle public funds and tax violations are Diana 
Stuller, 31, the former legislative analyst's office employee; Willie Cabrera, 
39, a former employee of Davis Travel Service, and Patricia Rommel, 32, 
Stuller's sister. Agents said Stuller and Cabrera are accused of illegally 
charging the analyst's office for more than $28,000 worth of airline tickets. 
Stuller also is charged with forging state checks totaling $86,445. 
</P>
</TEXT>
