<P>
AILING ATLANTA ARCHBISHOP MAY HAVE TO STEP DOWN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ATLANTA 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Archbishop Eugene A. Marino, the nation's highest-ranking black Roman Catholic 
clergyman, is suffering from physical problems and psychological stresses that 
could require he step down, a spokesman said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
Marino, 56, was in New York for meetings last month when he began suffering 
chest pains, the Rev. Peter Dora said. He remains at a retreat center in New 
York, where he is being treated by two physicians and a psychiatrist, the 
spokesman for the Atlanta archdiocese said. 
</P>
