<HEADLINE>
<P>
FOR THE RECORD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Santa Paula shooting -- An item on Sunday's Week in Review page incorrectly 
stated that Delfino Enricos Lopez, 43, of Santa Paula was accused in the 
shooting of a neighbor May 28. Lopez had been arrested on suspicion of murder 
after the shooting, but he was released Friday after prosecutors said they had 
insufficient evidence to prove he had committed a crime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Correction 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA060490-0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 228802 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
June 4, 1990, Monday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 3; Column 1; Metro Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
381 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: COSTA MESA; 
</P>
<P>
LOWRIDERS DRAW HIGH PRAISE AT SHOW 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MATT LAIT 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Mike Ramos looked at the restored dark green 1948 Chevrolet Fleetwood, complete 
with the optional dash electric razor, that his car club was displaying at 
Sunday's second annual Salsa Custom Lowrider Show and Family Fiesta, and beamed 
with what he called "Latino pride." 
</P>
<P>
"This is all part of our culture," said the 28-year-old vice president of the 
Orange County chapter of the Dukes. "It's not involved with gangs, it's safe 
and it's a good investment." 
</P>
<P>
Whether they had classic oldies like Ramos' club's or the newer "tricked-out" 
mini-trucks equipped with hydraulic, jumping suspensions and exotic paint jobs, 
the exhibitors at the show said the cars are much more than just unique sets of 
wheels. 
</P>
<P>
"It's a whole lifestyle," boasted 29-year-old Art Vazicaion, who owns a yellow, 
1984 Isuzu truck with an $8,000 stereo system. 
</P>
<P>
More than 20,000 people attended the show at the Orange County Fairgrounds. It 
featured not only cars and trucks but also authentic Latino food, art, crafts, 
music and dance. 
</P>
<P>
"It's really cool to walk around here. There's lots to see," said Rosa Mera, 
16, of El Toro. "The guys are pretty cute too." 
</P>
<P>
But for the most part, the 500 vehicles were the main attraction. 
</P>
<P>
Alfonzo Serrano showed passers-by his cousin's lowriding 1978 Cadillac Coup de 
Ville painted psychedelic colors. 
</P>
<P>
"He's put at least $15,000 into this," Serrano said. "There's chrome on the 
brakes and 14-karat gold on parts underneath the car." Pointing to the apricot 
interior he said, "These seats alone cost $3,000." 
</P>
<P>
In addition to the traditional lowriding Chevrolet Impalas, there were 
Mercedeses, Porsches, BMWs and even Suzuki Samurais built to hug the pavement. 
</P>
<P>
Rick Woods was showing off a 1988 white Mercedes with flashy gold rims and 
about a six-inch ground clearance. 
</P>
<P>
"I do these conversions for a living," he said. He smiled as he looked at the 
car, which he charged a man in Tennessee $22,000 to customize. "I'm not saying 
it's done in good taste or bad taste . . . this one is a little gaudy." 
</P>
<P>
Mini-truck lowriders with high riding hydraulic beds were also a big draw. 
</P>
<P>
"It's really amazing what these trucks can do," said Jeanne Sleeper, a 
spokeswoman for Inter-Shows, which organized the event. "They shoot up into the 
air and do 360s," she said. MATT LAIT 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Richard Cigarroa of Baldwin Park puts his truck through maneuvers during 
a hydraulic bed dancing contest at the Salsa Custom Lowrider Show. KEN HIVELY / 
Los Angeles Times 
</P>
